On the tumulus’s summit, the Sanpen Inari Shrine is enshrined. The mound is a distorted square measuring between 20 and 25 meters on each side, and is surrounded by a peripheral moat approximately 5–7 meters wide. In 1962 (Showa 37), a stone bead made of jade (碧玉) and a slanted-edge mirror (鼉龍鏡) were excavated from the mound and from the tea fields on its western side. In 1985 (Showa 60), as part of the Saitama Prefecture History compilation project, an excavation survey focused on confirming the moat was conducted, and earthenware vessels (土師器) with pre-fired bottom perforations were excavated from the moat. Based on the characteristics of the burial goods, the mound is dated to the late 4th century. The burial goods were designation1 as city-designation1 tangible cultural properties by Kawagoe City on January 29, 1988.<ref>{{Cite web|author=教育委員会 教育総務部 文化財保護課 管理担当|url=https://www.city.kawagoe.saitama.jp/kurashi/bunkakyoyo/bunkazai/shiteibunkazai/shishiteibunkazai/sanpenninari.html|title=市指定有形文化財 三変稲荷神社古墳出土品|work=Kawagoe City, Saitama Prefecture|date=2023-12-11|accessdate=2024-04-24}}</ref>

